# general_linear_group
## introduction
%%visits: 2
These are all the invertible matrices, all the matrices with non-zero determinants
## intuition
It is a group.

## rigour
$GL(n,\mathbb{C}) = \{A \in M_n(\mathbb{C} | \det(A) \neq 0\}$

Theorem. $GL(n,\mathbb{C}) \to \mathbb{C}^{\times}$ is surjective.
$GL(n,\mathbb{R}) \to \mathbb{R}^{\times}$ is surjective.

The [[centre_of_a_group|centre]] of the general_linear_group is isomorphic to $\mathbb{C}^{\times}$ 
    - Proof: See the lecture notes, but suffice to say, that the centre is only scaled identity matrices. We chose intereting Bs so that the commutative element AB = BA is singled out. See the lecture notes.
Outline of the proof, the centre [[centre_of_a_group|centre]] is only diagonal matrices.
